column1: 144217;instagram;2018-12-03 17:33:41;FALSE;"short story of dirty word music video:

maddie ( @madbanduk ) and i worked on this music video for quite some time to present her as an artist musician. she was influenced by #metoo campaign when writing the song. i was thrilled when she asked me to direct a #musicvideo for this amazing song : #dirtyword
you may see some gentle references to #samuelbeckett ‚Äúnot i‚Äù
i believe these references have the potential to trigger creating a beautiful image as well as interrupting a peaceful condition.
i chose to place her behind frames to make her an object of sight and used #kaleidoscope effect to manifest her statement visually.
i was too lucky to have my fantastic director of photography @cihan712
column2: incredible digital magician @guneyvai syncing with my mind and editing this madness
column3: my dear impressive producer @memetalialabora and the two multitasking set/makeup/ ‚Äúenablers of pretty much anything‚Äù duo @melin_edo & @uyurum and of course my best friend
column5: my constructive critic&supervisor @ustuncanga and maddie‚Äôs mom gigi who appeared like a fairy and added so many colourful layers to every detail in the set.

now we are craving for more as a gang!";;en;#metoo

column1: 144299;instagram;2018-12-03 18:41:05;FALSE;"this week we are looking at common safety behaviors parents need to adhere to for the safety of their child(ren).

i was at a hotel recently and i noticed a mom sent her son into the restroom by himself and even walked away from the door and entered a conference room. i cringed because my first thought was how do you know there isn't a child molester on the other side of that door? i see this all the time! and
column2: it isn't a knock against anyone's parenting skills
column3: it's an observation about how many parents aren't considering the dangers that lurk around them everyday
column4: and how safety is often assumed based on factors such as the demographics of the neighborhood
column5: the location you're in at the time
column6: who is around you and what you perceive their intent toward your child might be - things that have absolutely nothing to do with whether a predator can be just waiting for you to turn your head so they can strike. so
column7: the next time your child has to go to the restroom and you can't enter
column8: consider walking right up to the door and have your child open the door and you yell out ""is there anyone in here?"" wait for a response and if there is none
column9: hold the door ajar and have your child enter and actually yell out to you if they see anyone (including feet under the stall). if it's all clear
column10: let them use the restroom while you guard the door. if by chance someone is in there and your child can wait a minute
column11: allow the bathroom to clear out before you send them in. if that's not possible
column12: stand at the door and let the occupants know you are going to stand there with the door ajar enough to hear your child's voice and periodically ask them if they're ok until they're done. this may seem extreme to some
column13: but it only takes a minute for a predator to strike and public bathrooms have proven to provide a perfect opportunity. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate";;en;#childsexabuseawareness

column1: 144329;instagram;2018-12-03 19:13:26;FALSE;"@arimelber ‚ù§ @joyannreid üí™üòòüëç qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv
column2: completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

column1: that‚Äôs what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him ‚Äúwe can take it.‚Äù no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it‚Äôs a little thing
column2: just part of the story we are all interacting with.

column1: the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters
column2: then it‚Äôs easy to come along for the ride. there‚Äôs no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they‚Äôre both just characters on the television.

column1: that‚Äôs what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it‚Äôs not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it‚Äôs that we‚Äôve lost the capacity to treat civics
column3: and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters

column1: 144333;instagram;2018-12-03 19:16:22;FALSE;"@arimelber ‚ù§ @seanhannity üí™üòéüëç wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014
column2: when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

column1: documents show the john bolton super pac
column2: which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton
column4: 700 in 2014 for ""behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging."" those services included strategies that broke individual voters into ""clusters"" based on what messages would resonate with them.

column1: wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign
column2: such as ""drain the swamp"" and imagery of walls. ""a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014

column1: he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. ""everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval
column3: who left the company in late 2014.

column2: painful memory. and man.. i am triggered today! ‚ö†Ô∏è raw post ahead ‚ö†Ô∏è once i was trapped in my own home. once i was pinned to the ground when he sat on my chest. once i was held against the wall by my shoulders. once i was thrown across the room when i tried to get out the window. once i was scared and didn‚Äôt know what to do or who to talk to. once i woke up and i walked away. domestic violence comes in all shapes and sizes. physical and mental. you never know what someone is facing or how they are coping. all we can do is have an open heart and be there when the time comes. i‚Äôve always been willing to share my dark corners and be open so long as it could help another. i was strong enough to walk away.. but that‚Äôs just the beginning. there‚Äôs many reasons why i chose the lifestyle i lead now
column3: the majority of which being health and wellness. but i would be lying if i said i didn‚Äôt look at my growth and feel a bit more confident in who i am and knowing i could hold my own. #awareness

last sunday (two days back) was tedx women 2018 and it was one heck of a day. i was in the registrations team and things went pretty smoothly alhamdulillah.
the talks were amazing and especially the one by miss tanzeela (first african mpa in sindh)
column2: i was very inspired by the talk. fun fact: her urdu was very good! -

column1: the evening ended on a good note and with the hope of we as a nation giving back the rights to women which they deserve
column2: and moreover than rights the position that we need them to be in rather than what society has told us for centuries. -

column1: i pray we grow as a nation for days to come in a better way. ameen!

column1: 144600;instagram;2018-12-04 01:39:38;FALSE;"just  thought that i needed to say something about this because it's a pretty serious matter and it really will hopefully get some awareness spread.... so about 2 weeks ago i was at a party where a bunch of homophobic people where ( i didn't really know this at the time) i was there with my now gf jazz( jasmine she's awesome) so word got out that i was trans and a lot of them started bombarding me with questions
column2: well this one dude ( whos name will be changed) tyler was really upset
column3: ( violence and rape stated ahead) he through me over his shoulder and ran out in the woods with me and he started to take his clothes off and then he took my clothes off. he had a pocket knife on him so he cut my pants and my hoodie including my t-shirt and i wouldn't be able to wear them again
column4: the only thing he didn't get off of me was my binder. i'm not going to go into to much detail because it gets really violent. so i heard my girlfriend yell my name and that's when he duck taped my mouth shut. he used something ( i think it was his pocket knife) and cut my arms. he had saw my self harm scars and told me that since i was such an idiot for cutting before that i deserved it. well when he heard police sirens he ran off and i was only covered by a thin blanket. i was taken to the police station since that was probably the safest place for me since my parents were out of town. well we were locked in a soundproof room the next day and long story short i was raped again by tyler... i was later taken to a hospital where i was tested and the results came back today and i should be fine but
column5: i had 2 fractured ribs and i can't wear a binder for 6-8 weeks because of the risk of having to much pressure on my chest.

column1: i'd like to take this opportunity to talk about some experiences with sexual harassment

column2: i wore a sports jacket every day. i would seldom take off this protective layer
column3: because it was my first survival tactic for preventing sexual harassment from peers and older men
column4: at school & in the streets. in retrospect
column5: i wonder what could have been if as young girls we were to come together
column7: and act in solidarity by disrupting & dismantling sexual harassment together at an early age.

column2: i caught glimpses of what this could look like. i have had women save me from men following me on the street. once
column3: i was being followed at night & literally prayed my way into fast food place. i was offered sanctuary by a latina migrant worker
column4: despite the dine-in area being closed. another instance
column5: i was waiting at a bus stop. a man pulled up & tried to solicit sex. when the light turned green
column6: a woman rolled up in her suv & shouted
column7: ""are you ok? is this man bothering you!? do you need a ride?"" & the man drove off immediately! both these instances
column9: have demonstrated the effectiveness of sisterhood & taking direct action against sexual harassment. but what about a more collective strategy for feminist movement & achieving women's liberation?

column1: writing has been a part of my life for as long as i can remember. english class was always a favorite
column2: and from poetry to prose - my pen recorded memories

column1: as life would have it though i headed down the road to hospitality and my writing became part-time. however
column2: thanks to a friend - i wrote down some life goals in my early college years.... he told me that putting everything down on paper made a difference; that our subconscious took it a little more seriously. dreams vs goals.
somewhere around 19/20 years old i wrote down that my goal was to be published by 30 years old. .

column1: i have written many pieces over the year. but my biggest obstacle has always been myself. it takes courage to put your writing out there. and as a result most of what i have written has gone unseen.

column3: i found myself suddenly immersed in a sea of brave women
column4: and i felt compelled to write a piece of my story. and with that

column1: on january 13th - a little over a month before i completed my 30th year - ‚Äúbuilding my wall
column2: brick by brick‚Äù was posted. little did i imagine that my first published piece would be on a subject so important
column4: as the article i wrote for @cherrybombe. nor did i think that my article would have such a positive impact on others. friends who i share a daily life with opened up about their experiences. we had never spoken about certain things before. not that it was taboo for us - but instead it had become so norm that it was often overlooked. .

column1: so thank you to cherry bombe for helping me find my voice and my courage this year. and thank you for continuing to support women in our industry. üíó .

what a week it has been.
overwhelming in so many ways and such a range of emotions experienced.
i was so nervous and fearful about a backlash based on the past negative reactions of doubt
column3: blame i experienced in the past when i actually found the courage to share.

column1: i have been holding my breath and each time i read an encouraging word
column2: a message of solidarity and a sincere
column3: heartfelt message i breathe a little easier and each kind message has been so deeply healing and i feel years of hurt unravel into something softer. so thank you each one of you who took the heart and effort to reach out.

column2: i send love and hugs. if they need more support
column3: they can call aware: women‚Äôs helpline 1800 777 5555; sexual assault care centre 6779 0282

column1: there have been some negative comments that we received. there have also been people who try to take advantage of the situation. i am not surprised as when we speak of #truth there are bound to be people who experience discomfort or who are opportunists or make it all about them. i recognise that they too are suffering for them to leave such comments and for reacting with ego and to them i send love and healing.

column2: we are not victims. we are #survivors. sexual violence is never about sex
column3: it is about #power. or rather the illusion of false power. men who feel powerless or intimidated often attack women who intimidate them or say no to them. because they want to take away that woman‚Äôs power. women and children are not vulnerable

column1: 144894;instagram;2018-12-04 10:20:12;FALSE;"@thejimmydoreshow @foxnews @cnn @democracynow @cnn @nbcnews @bbcnews @helsinginsanomat qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv
column2: completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

column1: that‚Äôs what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him ‚Äúwe can take it.‚Äù no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it‚Äôs a little thing
column2: just part of the story we are all interacting with.

column1: the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters
column2: then it‚Äôs easy to come along for the ride. there‚Äôs no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they‚Äôre both just characters on the television.

column1: 144956;instagram;2018-12-04 12:03:35;FALSE;"our structures work better for those in the centre of power. the people most in need of protection don't know they exist or worry if they engage in them they will lose their access to their livelihood"". anita hill

i remember coming from school and being glued to the tv watching anita hill testify about sexual harassment she was subjected to. she was the first person i ever heard talk about sexual violence and her courage gave me hope. hearing her speak yesterday about the structures that uphold sexual harassment and how we need to focus our work on those pushed to the margins was everything. i ended up bumping into her in the elevator and after i calmed down my heart we talked about the need to ensure black women
